---
// src/pages/about.astro
// export const prerender = true; — uncomment if this page never changes at runtime
import Page from '../layouts/Page.astro';
---
<Page
  title="I work at the intersection of strategy, systems, and execution."
  eyebrow="About · the longer story"
  lede="Two decades of translating complex missions into outcomes that hold up under scrutiny — across federal modernization, communications strategy, and digital infrastructure."
>
  <section class="section" data-screen-label="02 About — Body">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1.4fr; gap: 80px; align-items: start;">

        <!-- Portrait placeholder -->
        <div class="reveal" style="position: sticky; top: 120px;">
          <div class="media-frame tall" style="max-width: 420px;">
            <div class="placeholder-stripes"></div>
            <span class="label">Portrait · client-supplied</span>
          </div>
          <div style="margin-top: 24px; font-family: var(--mono-font); font-size: 11px; letter-spacing: 0.12em; color: var(--text-dim); text-transform: uppercase;">
            J. Michael Browning<br />
            <span style="color: var(--text-mute); margin-top: 6px; display: inline-block;">Washington, D.C.</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Body prose -->
        <div class="reveal">
          <div class="prose" style="margin: 0;">
            <p>
              I lead with discipline and urgency. The work I'm proudest of has nearly always
              looked the same from the outside — quiet, on schedule, unremarkable in the moment —
              and only later revealed itself as a structural shift.
            </p>
            <p>
              That's the bias of my practice. I don't optimize for the announcement. I optimize for
              what's still standing eighteen months after the press release stops circulating, when
              the team that inherits the work has to operate the thing for real.
            </p>
            <p>
              Most of my career has been spent inside high-stakes environments where the stakes
              aren't theoretical: federal agencies modernizing the systems citizens actually touch,
              crisis communications under live scrutiny, platform builds that have to ship on a
              date that doesn't move. I've been the strategist, the communicator, the engineer,
              and — when the room demanded it — the person who stays late to write the memo that
              gets the project unstuck.
            </p>
            <h2>How I think about the work</h2>
            <p>
              <strong>Trust is a system property.</strong> The most expensive failures I've watched
              were never failures of intelligence — they were failures of interface between teams
              who had each done their part correctly. I work the seams.
            </p>
            <p>
              <strong>Pace is a posture.</strong> I move with deliberate urgency. The cost of being
              late is almost always larger than the cost of deciding.
            </p>
            <p>
              <strong>Write it down.</strong> If a decision isn't recorded, it didn't happen — and
              I'll watch you re-litigate it for the next six months.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="mt-lg reveal">
            <a href="/contact" class="btn btn-primary">Start a conversation →</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Page>
